\section{Software Architecture}

The application is organised as a collection of JavaScript ES modules,
each responsible for a specific part of the interactive experience. The
architecture is centred around the \texttt{Experience} class, which acts
as the main coordinator and provides the shared references required by
the other components.

The application entry point, \texttt{main.js}, creates a single
\texttt{Experience} instance associated with the WebGL canvas. The class
implements a singleton-like pattern: if an instance already exists, the
same object is returned instead of creating a second application state.
This ensures that the scene, camera, renderer and world components share
a single consistent context.

\subsection{Core Application Structure}

During construction, \texttt{Experience} creates the main
\texttt{THREE.Scene} and initialises the utilities and subsystems required
by the application:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \texttt{Sizes}, which stores the current viewport dimensions and
    device pixel ratio;
    \item \texttt{Time}, which generates the continuous update events;
    \item \texttt{Camera}, which manages the perspective camera, controls
    and animated viewpoints;
    \item \texttt{Renderer}, which manages WebGL rendering and
    post-processing;
    \item \texttt{World}, which creates the environment and loads the main
    portfolio model;
    \item \texttt{RaycasterController}, which manages pointer-based
    interaction with the scene.
\end{itemize}

