The \texttt{World} class has a deliberately limited responsibility. It
creates an \texttt{Environment} instance and a \texttt{PortfolioModel}
instance, and forwards frame updates to the latter. The environment
configures the background, the scene environment map and the main
ambient, hemispherical, directional and point lights.

\subsection{Model Loading and Runtime Configuration}

The main scene is stored in the
\texttt{public/models/portfolio\_case.glb} file and is loaded
asynchronously by \texttt{PortfolioModel} through
\texttt{GLTFLoader}. Before the model becomes available, a simplified
placeholder scene is displayed. If the GLB file cannot be loaded, the
placeholder remains visible and the application reports a warning
instead of failing completely.

After loading, the model is processed through a sequence of specialised
components. \texttt{ApplyingTexture} assigns texture maps according to
mesh, material and parent names. \texttt{ModelMaterialSafety} isolates
and normalises imported material instances, while
\texttt{CozyLedMaterials}, \texttt{MaterialEnhancements} and
\texttt{PlantMaterialTint} apply further visual adjustments to selected
parts of the model.

The imported hierarchy is then inspected to identify the objects
required by the application. Meshes whose names begin with
\texttt{CLICK\_} are configured as invisible interaction targets, while
the visible meshes receive the appropriate shadow and material settings.
The same loading phase creates the animation and power-management
systems associated with Dummy, the lamp chain, the fans, the cooling
tubes and the illuminated computer components.

\subsection{Interaction Layer}

Interaction with the three-dimensional environment is managed by
\texttt{RaycasterController}. The controller uses a dedicated Three.js
layer containing only the intended click targets. This separates the
visible geometry from the interaction geometry and prevents decorative
or complex meshes from receiving unintended pointer events.

Pointer coordinates are converted from screen coordinates to normalized
device coordinates and used to construct a ray from the camera into the
scene. When an intersection is detected, the metadata stored in the
selected target determines the corresponding operation.

The lamp and chain targets are forwarded to \texttt{PowerExperience},
which controls the powered state of the scene. The other targets open a
portfolio section and request the corresponding camera transition.
For example, the CPU opens the About section, the GPU opens Projects,
the RAM opens Academic information, the fans open Work Experience and
the cables open Hobbies and Interests.

The textual interface is managed by \texttt{SectionPanel}. This class
controls the visibility and content of the HTML panel and provides
specialised layouts for academic experiences, projects and work
experience. Closing the panel triggers a callback that returns the
camera to the default view.

\subsection{Camera and Rendering Systems}

The camera system uses a \texttt{THREE.PerspectiveCamera} combined with
\texttt{OrbitControls}. Each interactive section has a predefined camera
position and target. When a section is selected, GSAP interpolates both
the camera position and the controls target, producing a smooth movement
towards the selected component. The controls are temporarily disabled
during the transition and enabled again when both interpolations are
complete.

The \texttt{Renderer} class creates the \texttt{WebGLRenderer} and
configures sRGB output, ACES Filmic tone mapping, antialiasing and shadow
maps. Rendering is extended through an \texttt{EffectComposer} pipeline
containing selective bloom, ambient occlusion and custom shader passes.
The selective bloom system renders the LED components separately and
composites their contribution over the base scene, preventing unrelated
objects from producing an excessive glow.

If a WebGL context cannot be created, the renderer hides the canvas and
shows a fallback message asking the user to use a compatible browser
with hardware acceleration enabled.

\subsection{Update and Resize Cycle}

The real-time update cycle is generated by the \texttt{Time} utility
through \texttt{requestAnimationFrame}. At each frame, it calculates the
elapsed time and the time difference from the previous frame, then emits
a \texttt{tick} event.

The \texttt{Experience} class responds to this event by executing the
following operations:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item update the camera controls;
    \item update the world and its active animations;
    \item update the raycasting controller;
    \item render the current frame.
\end{enumerate}

The \texttt{Sizes} utility listens for browser resize events and stores
the updated viewport dimensions. When a resize occurs, the camera aspect
ratio and projection matrix are recalculated, while the renderer and its
post-processing buffers are resized accordingly. The effective pixel
ratio is limited to reduce the rendering cost on high-density displays.

This modular organisation separates scene construction, rendering,
animation, interaction and interface management. As a result, the
behaviour of individual elements can be modified without concentrating
the entire application logic in a single script.


